segments.text: In 1932, this Sims Street was the Hearn Highway.
No, wait a minute.
Yes.
No?
Hearn Highway went up on Washington.
This was Table Road.
And it was gravel.
And this place here where this house is sitting in, it was a cotton field.
They raised cotton and corn here.
And when I bought this land here, it was still rose, oh, say, four or five inches high yet.
That's straight in the mile because the rose was standing here.
And the wire fence rolled up the wire and cleaned up, cleaned up the bar ditch.
There's lots of work here.
Do you know who owned this land?
Yes.
Well, I bought it.
I don't know who owned it then at the time of when they
when the field was in progress.
But I bought it from this real estate broker.
He was a lawyer.
He's dead now.
Well, I can't think of his name right now.
But he was a lawyer.
And his partner, who was a part-time owner of the

lumber company in that other end of town and i bought that from them and later on i bought that other lot i had uh work uh this land here the way that uh build it up but it was kind of low you know and then later on they they blocked up that street it didn't stay uh too long trucks broke the
like Ash Falls and all that.
Then, about six, seven years ago, they put that concrete on there because that made it real fine.
But the city limits, when I came here in Briner, was 10,000 in the city.
And the city limit was there at the corner of Sims and 15th Street.
That was the city limits then.
Well, back in
In 19, let me see, it was, I don't know, maybe 39, 40 city limits were up to the railroad track.
Now the city limits are kind of close to Benchley.
And it has grown considerably because between here and college,
It was a partner with Woods there.
Well, it was one or two houses, maybe three.
And it rebuilt the streets, College Avenue.
It was this Texas.
Texas Avenue used to be College Avenue.
And it run through college.
That was Highway 61 through Houston.
And then this other, now that
where it cuts off and College Avenue going to that Highway 6 now, it wasn't only a small street there.
I remember we had a little trail there to go through there, a short cut.
But we had College Avenue come around like that and make it in here.
And then they straightened up like that and went on.
But the year I left here in 1934,
Went to Houston.
And in those years, that's when all this happened.
Then I hit Huntsville, and I went to work for Chevrolet in Huntsville.
And, well, I used to come here every now and then, see my father and my mother.
I'd come at nighttime and go back at night.
So I wasn't aware of what was going on.
But then when I moved to Bryan and back with my family in 42,
Well, then I noticed that Brian has grown quite a lot.
And they built this Brian Field, and there's a lot going on.
And since then, it has grown so much that I'll have to, sometimes I get called to go start a car somewhere.
I'll have to find it in the mail before I go.
It's getting where, well, I know Brian pretty good, but now and then, I'll have to.
I have to look in the map to find the places and where they are and all that.
